voice_to_text: Turns out being invisible is such a terrifying experience, the experimenters first poured glue next to the man and then spread it evenly on his face. Then they used a fan to dry the glue quickly. When the glue set, they cut a hole with a knife. After that, they added a pair of glasses. They originally thought John could only hold out for a few days at most, but they didn't expect him to be stuck in the lab. As time went by, John got more and more irritable. Finally, one day, he escaped. When John got home, he saw his neighbor changing clothes at home. However, at the crucial moment, the woman pulled up the curtain. John looked at himself in the mirror and suddenly realized he had the ability to be invisible. This meant he could do whatever he wanted. So just after the woman finished taking a shower, there was a knock on the door. The woman walked to the door but found there was nothing outside. She thought it might be her imagination, but unexpectedly, the doorbell rang again. The next second, the woman was a bit confused and then walked to the door and opened it, but the corridor was empty. However, just then, John sneaked into the woman's house without making a sound.

voice_to_text: I'm doing it, your hand. No magic comes from nothing. The teacher lifted a bouquet. The flowers wilted instantly. A stone rose into the air. My classmates copied her. Their stones floated in the air. I tried again and again. I failed. Every time teacher came up to me, she scolded me for rushing, for trying to use magic to make myself pretty. I was born with a curved spine. My mouth was crooked. I was ugly. In class, I was always the slowest. I broke down. I looked at myself in the mirror. I sobbed out loud. The next day, the teacher took us to the seagull tower. She told us to hold up bottles to catch lightning. Dora went first. She lifted her bottle carefully. The lightning knocked her out. Annie went next. She hesitated for a moment. She caught the lightning. The bottle shattered. When it was my turn, I gave the teacher a cold glance. I gathered my courage. I raised the bottle high. Lightning struck my chest. It slammed me into the wall. I watched the other succeed. I kept failing. I saw the disappointment in the teacher's eyes. I felt utterly insignificant. Humiliation, resentment, they flooded me. Anger lit up inside me. The teacher saw my potential. She told me inner beauty is the true beauty. She told me not to let anger consume me. That night, the teacher took the girls who failed the exam away. I followed secretly. I watched her turn. The three students into eels. She already knew I was behind her, she told me. She only took away their control. They would provide energy for the academy like flowers. Their best purpose was to wither. Right after the teacher prepared to give me a flawless face, I stared at my ugly reflection. She told me to close my eyes to imagine the most beautiful woman in the world. And then.

voice_to_text: My sister in law threatened to steal my unborn child using her fake grief, so I helped her grief become real. My brother's wife, Diana, discovered her ultimate weapon the day she lost her first pregnancy. If someone questioned her spending, she'd clutch her stomach and call them insensitive. If anyone in the family shared good news, she'd leave the room wailing that their happiness was triggering her grief. If my brother asked her to help with anything, she'd collapse on the couch claiming the stress could cause another loss. The manipulation quickly went from tears to total destruction. First, Diana got my mom's 60th birthday party canceled by claiming the pink decorations triggered her loss. Mom spent her milestone birthday comforting Diana instead. When my cousin announced her pregnancy, Diana screamed that we were rubbing fertility in her face and claimed the shock caused her to have a panic attack. My cousin hid her entire pregnancy in shame. Then Diana wanted a 70 thousand dollar Mercedes, but my brother said no. So she staged a total breakdown at the dealership, wailing about needing a safe car for her rainbow baby and threatened to divorce if my brother didn't buy it. She didn't spare me either and went all out during my wedding planning. Diana called all my vendors claiming my flower choices would trigger miscarriages, posted on wedding forms that I was a baby killer, and demanded I change my date because it was near her loss anniversary. When I refused. She told family members that my selfishness had caused her to lose twins, and I know it might be hard to believe, but she went even further. I was four months pregnant and had managed to hide it from everyone except Diana, who'd noticed my subtle changes. One morning, she ambushed me at a doctor's appointment with an offer that made my blood freeze. I know you're pregnant, she said calmly. Here's what's going to happen. You're going to tell everyone you're carrying a baby for me as a surrogate. You'll give birth, hand the baby to me, and I'll finally be the mother. Everyone pities me for not being. I laughed, thinking she was joking, but she wasn't. If you refuse, I'll tell everyone you've been mocking my miscarriages throughout your pregnancy. She showed me her phone with drafted emails to my employer about my workplace harassment regarding her infertility, and even had screenshots of edited text where I called her an infertile bitch. She'd been planning this for weeks. I smiled sweetly when she saw how horrified I was and added, besides, you can always have another one. Standing there with my hand protectively over my bump, realizing Diana literally wanted to steal my child, I felt rage unlike anything before. I knew Diana's weakness was her need to maintain her victim story at all costs. She'd already sent me those fake texts and threatened emails, not knowing she was handing me evidence. So I did Something simple. I scheduled a meeting with my brother at his office, saying I needed to discuss the surrogacy arrangement Diana had proposed. When he arrived, confused, I broke down crying and showed him Diana's threatening text about taking my baby. I'm scared she'll hurt herself or the baby if I don't give in. She keeps saying this is her only chance at motherhood. My brother's face went white. He checked the time stamps on her threats and said, wait, these are from yesterday morning when she was with me at the mall. The realisation broke him. His wife had been plotting to steal his sister's baby while shopping right beside him. voice_to_text: People who've been kidnapped, how did you survive? I was 12 when a man in a blue pickup truck pulled up next to me while I was walking home from school. He asked if I wanted to earn $20 helping him move boxes. My parents had always warned me about strangers, but $20 seems like a fortune to a kid who got $5 allowance. The the moment I got in his truck, I knew I'd made a terrible mistake. He immediately locked the doors and started driving in the opposite direction of where he said we were going. When I asked where we were headed, he told me to shut up and sit still. He drove for what felt like hours to a small cabin in the woods. No neighbours, no cell towers, nothing but trees. He dragged me inside and tied me to a chair in what looked like a basement. The smell was awful, like something had died down there. For the first two days, he barely spoke to me except to bring stale bread and warm water. I cried constantly, begging him to let me go home. He just stared at me with these cold, empty eyes and said my parents probably hadn't even noticed I was gone yet. On the third day, he made a mistake. He left his phone on the table while he went upstairs to make himself lunch. I could hear him moving around in the kitchen above me. Rope around my wrists, Had loosened slightly from struggling, and I managed to work one hand free. I grabbed his phone and called the first number I could think of, my mom's work number that she'd made me memorize for emergencies. When she answered, I whispered as quietly as I could, mom, I've been kidnapped in a cabin somewhere. There are tall pine trees everywhere, and I can hear a train in the distance. Before I could say more, I heard his footsteps coming down the stairs. I quickly put the phone back and got my hand back in the rope just as he appeared. He looked at me suspiciously, but didn't seem to notice anything different. What I didn't know was that my mom had immediately called the police while staying on the line. They traced the call and started searching for cabins near train tracks in our area. Meanwhile, she kept calling his phone every few minutes, hoping I'd answer the next morning. He seemed agitated, kept looking out the windows and pacing around the cabin. I realised later that police helicopters had been circling the area, getting closer to finding us. He started talking about moving me somewhere else, which terrified me. That afternoon, he went outside to load something into his truck. I heard him talking to someone on the phone, getting angry. While he was distracted, I noticed he'd left the basement door unlocked. This was my chance. I quietly climbed the stairs and saw him through the window. Still arguing on the phone by his truck. The front door was about 15 feet away. I knew I had to be smart about this. If I ran straight out, he'd see me immediately. Instead, I crawled on my hands and knees toward the back of the cabin. There was a small window near the floor that looks like it might be big enough for me to squeeze through. I managed to push it open and wiggle through, scraping my arms and legs on the frame. Once outside, I ran as fast as I could toward the sound of the train tracks. I figured if I could reach them, I might find help, or at least know which direction LED back to civilization. My legs felt like jelly from being tied up for days, but pure adrenaline kept me moving. After running for about 10 minutes, I heard dogs barking in the distance. Then I heard voices calling my name. It was the search and rescue team my mom had called in. I screamed as loud as I could and kept running toward the voices. A police officer

voice_to_text: She cheated on me with 6 different guys while we were dating each other. So if I were you, bro, I would be careful. He raised an eyebrow and explained that he was only there to get free food and to try to make me jealous enough to give her another chance. It was the stupidest thing I had heard. I looked over at my ex's face was super red with embarrassment and realized that it was actually true. I felt a serious rush of ego boost, but at the same time, I felt something unexpected too. Like, dude, call me stupid. But I felt pretty touched that she would go this far just to try to win me back. It definitely wasn't the best way to win me back, but definitely creative. So I told her jokingly that if she really wanted me back, she should try showing up here alone for another month to prove that she really meant it. I walked off to finish the rest of my shift. After that, she really did show up every day with a book or journal sitting at the same booth waiting for my shift to finish. I didn't even really talk to her much and she still came around. Weeks went by and on the last day of the month, she walked into Waffle House with a huge smile on her face. I walked over with her usual order and sat beside her in the booth. She asked me, If I would finally be her boyfriend again. I smiled back and said, absolutely not. I reminded her that she cheated on me with several guys and one of them was my best friend. She picked up the glass of water and thought about splashing it all over me. Instead, she splashed water on her own face to wake herself up and left, angrily ripping up one of the menus in the restaurant out of frustration before walking out the front door. The entire angry scene was crazy cute, like, ah, there goes my little Harley Quinn. I grinned and told my manager that I was finally quitting. I chased after her and apologized, saying that I wanted to get back at her a little for the horrible mess she put me through before I unzipped my jacket and wrapped it around her head to help her stay warm. After seeing water still drip down from her hair, I took her home that night and we talked about setting new boundaries if we wanted the relationship to work better this time. To this day, we're still together and no longer the toxic kids we used to be. Also for our prenup, we had a fun photo shoot at that same Waffle House, forever reminding us of our ridiculous and petty days.

voice_to_text: At noon, the doorbell rang and mom flew to answer feverishly. An exhausted woman stood there clutching her purse, thanking mom over and over for babysitting. Behind her, a girl about 11 with dark hair hung back, clearly uneasy. Take all the time you need, mom purred in a voice I'd never heard before. The second their car turned the corner, something in Mom's face shifted into pure predator. She grabbed the girl's wrist hard enough to leave marks and dragged her toward Daniela's room. Welcome home, baby. The girl's confusion turned to fear. My name is not Daniela. It's Katie, she, I whispered. The sound of Mom's palm hitting her face made me flinch. You are Daniela, Mom shrieked. Everything accelerated into a nightmare. Mom commanded Katie to undress, but when she shook her head, mom grabbed the Scissors from Daniela's desk. Katie tried to bolt, but mom caught her by the hair. I watched frozen in horror as she cut through Katie's clothes with violent precision, humming Daniela's lullaby. Katie stood there exposed and sobbing while mom forced Daniela's tiny dress over her head. Bathroom became a torture chamber. Mom dragged the screaming girl in while I watched in horror. Through the mirror, I watched mom slather bleach on her hair. I want my mommy, she wailed. I am your mommy. Mom, god gave you back to me. In one desperate moment, when mom turned for more dye, Katie scooped bleach and smeared it across Mom's eyes. Mom's Scream was inhuman as she clawed at her face. Katie sprinted out and yelled for help. I flew downstairs and dove into the pantry with my phone. I whispered frantically to 9, 1, 1 while Katie sobs mixed with Mom's rage above us. Those minutes waiting for sirens felt like hours. When they finally broke down Daniela's door, they found mom sitting calmly on the bed, brushing both Katie's hair and the dolls. My two danielas have finally met, she announced it's proudly. Katie threw herself at the officers while mom fought like a wild animal, screaming, don't take my babies again, even as they wrestled her into handcuffs. The little girl's mom placed a restraining order on our family and Mom's been institutionalized 8 months now. Last time I visited, she grabbed my hand and whispered, I forgive you for sending Daniela away again. She smiled and for a moment I thought I saw a glimpse of mom I had before the crash until she mentioned another patient had Daniela's exact laugh. After that, dad and I cleaned out Daniela's room together and donated everything, including that horrible doll.

voice_to_text: What made you call the police on your own mother? My seven year old sister Daniela was singing in the back seat behind me when a truck ran the red light and slammed into us at top speed. By the time the car stopped flipping, Daniela became permanently silent. After hours trying to save her, the doctors told us she was gone. Mom climbed into the hospital bed and pulled Daniela against her chest, rocking her for three hours. Mommy's here, baby. Dad just stood frozen when the nurses pried my sister from Mom's arms. And while they fought, I threw up, knowing I survived and Daniela didn't. The first few weeks blurred together with mom crying in Danielle's room for hours. Dad would hold her shoulders and whisper that everything would be okay. I kept making her chamomile tea, but the cups always went cold on the nightstand. She couldn't stop staring at Danielle things long enough to drink them. Our grief therapist said this was normal and everyone processes loss differently. So we didn't worry when mom started making Daniela's bed every morning. Or arrange the stuffed animals in perfect rows, just how Daniela liked them. We thought maybe this ritual was helping her cope with the loss. The day Daniela would have turned 9, mom showed up with a wrapped birthday present, saying she'd already bought it before the accident. An obvious lie, but dad and I let it slide because what harm could one gift do To an already broken family. A month later, mom walked through the door carrying a life size doll that looked exactly like Daniela, with real human hair and her exact shade. She sat me down to show how she could brush his hair, just like Daniela's bedtime routine. I forced myself to nod, my heart breaking from the desperate sight. The next few days spiraled out of control. Mom dressed the doll in new outfits every morning and took it everywhere in Daniela's wagon. She did both voices like the doll could actually respond. People at the mall grabbed their children and hurried away from us. Dad found the three thousand dollar credit card charge. When he confronted her, she clutched the doll, screaming, you can't put a price on our daughter! He started sleeping on the couch that night. Things got worse when she pulled me out of school claiming it was too dangerous. She set up homeschooling with three play settings at our kitchen table. Week after week, I sat there watching her teach that doll alongside me. Until one morning I couldn't take it anymore. One morning I finally snapped and said, stop it! Daniela is gone! Mom sobbed. You abandoned her in that car and now you're doing it again! The guilt hit me so hard I couldn't breathe. I'm here too, I mumbled, while she cradled that doll like a real child, while tears streamed down her face. Two weeks after dad left, mom started Acting strange, she'd leave the doll behind and disappear, returning with stories about her wonderful new friend and the woman's precious daughter. I found her phone with Daniela's photo replaced by a stranger's child. She has Daniela's exact laugh, mom said. Behind me, her eyes.

Behind her, a girl about 11 with dark hair hung back, clearly uneasy. Take all the time you need, mom purred in a voice I'd never heard before. The second their car turned the corner, something in Mom's face shifted into pure predator. She grabbed the girl's wrist hard enough to leave marks and dragged her toward Daniela's room. Welcome home, baby. The girl's confusion turned to fear. My name is not Daniela. It's Katie, she, I whispered. The sound of Mom's palm hitting her face made me flinch. You are Daniela, Mom shrieked. Everything accelerated into a nightmare. Mom commanded Katie to undress, but when she shook her head, mom grabbed the Scissors from Daniela's desk. Katie tried to bolt, but mom caught her by the hair. I watched frozen in horror as she cut through Katie's clothes with violent precision, humming Daniela's lullaby. In one desperate moment, when mom turned for more dye, Katie scooped bleach and smeared it across Mom's eyes. Mom's Scream was inhuman. As she clawed at her face, Katie sprinted out and yelled for help. I flew downstairs and dove into the pantry with my phone. I whispered frantically to 9, 1, 1 while Katie sobs mixed with Mom's rage above us. Those minutes waiting for sirens felt like hours. When they finally broke down Daniela's door, they found mom sitting calmly on the bed, brushing both Katie's hair and the dolls. My two danielas have finally met, she announced proudly. Katie threw herself at the officers while mom fought like a wild animal, screaming, don't take my babies again, even as they wrestled her into handcuffs. Last time I visited, she grabbed my hand and whispered, I forgive you for sending Daniela away again. voice_to_text: On my birthday, my family gave me a thoughtful gift. When I opened it, I found a notice telling me to move out of my own house. I smiled and a few months later returned the favor at their wedding. My 30th birthday started like any other family gathering. Mom insisted on hosting at my place because, quote, your house has the best space for everyone. I should have seen it coming. My younger brother Henry and his fiance Ashley showed up first, followed by my parents and extended family. Everyone seemed weirdly excited, exchanging knowing glances. Then came the moment before Cake. Mom announced, we have a very special gift for you, sweetheart. Ashley handed me an elegantly wrapped box with a bow. The room went silent as I untied the ribbon. Inside was a single envelope. No card, no note, just legal paperwork, 60 day notice to vacate my own house. I looked up slowly. Henry was grinning. Surprise, we bought your house. What? I said, still processing. Well, technically, we made an offer to mom and dad. Ashley chimed in. Since they co signed your mortgage five years ago, they're technically co owners. They agreed to sell us their share, which gives us majority ownership. So legally you're the tenant now. My mother smiled sweetly. We. this would be perfect for Henry and Ashley to start their marriage. You're always traveling for work anyway. You don't really need all this space. This is my house. I said quietly, I've paid every single mortgage payment for five years. Dad shrugged, but we're on the deed. That makes it partly ours. We're just exercising our rights. Henry leaned back smug. Don't make this dramatic, Ryan. Ashley and I need a real home for our future kids. You're single. You can rent somewhere smaller. The rage inside me was volcanic, but something else took over, cold calculation. I smiled. Wow, this is incredibly thoughtful. Everyone relaxed, interpreting my calm as acceptance. See, mom said, I knew you'd understand once you thought about it. I nodded, slowly setting the notice down. When's the wedding again? June 15th, Ashley said proudly at the Botanical Gardens. It's going to be magical. Can't wait, I replied, still smiling. That night, I called my real estate lawyer.

voice_to_text: She sat me down with this rehearsed speech about how we'd grown apart, how she needed to find herself, how this was best for both of us. I want a divorce, she said, not quite meeting my eyes. I nodded slowly, okay, I'll have my lawyer contact yours. Her face lit up, not with sadness, with relief. She even let a small smile slip. That's when I knew I'd made the right call. Her lawyer sent the initial filing three days later. The demands were breathtaking. Half of everything, including my business, spousal support for five years, the house, even my grandfather's inheritance that she'd never been entitled to. We attached the photos of her notebook, the calculations, the planning. Most devastating was the evidence of her affair, because once I started looking, I found it. Was this a mistake, too? Her face went pale. The final settlement was nothing like her original demands. No business stake, no inheritance, no spousal support, just an even split of actual marital assets. And she had to cover her own legal fees. Last week, she sent me a long email about how I manipulated everything, how I planned this from the beginning, how I was vindictive and cruel. I read it once, then deleted it. And that evening he wrapped all eight arms around my forearm to gently pull crab from my beating tongues. His massive 200 pound body moved with surprising Grace through the crystal clear water of his tank. But when any other keeper approached, the same gentle creature became a destructive nightmare that sprayed black ink everywhere and destroyed thousands of dollars it's worth of equipment. Our new operations director Caroline watched from the observation deck with her arms crossed, clearly unimpressed by what she called my animal dependency problem during yesterday's staff meeting. She believed every creature should have multiple handlers because no single employee should be irreplaceable, especially not because of some oversized sea creature that cost more than most people's houses. Caroline had spent three weeks documenting every minor violation she could manage. Manufacturer writing me up for wearing a different brand of reef safe sunscreen than the one corporate required even though their brand gave me hives and docking my pay. When Poseidon's complex eating routine ran five minutes over my scheduled break, her masterpiece was hiring Tim, her former assistant manager who spent entire shifts taking Instagram selfies near the shark tank and had never worked with cephalopods in his 24 years of existence. Poseidon hated Tim with a burning intensity of a thousand suns shooting Pressurized water jets that soaked him completely whenever he approached the tank. And once Tim slipped so dramatically on the wet observation deck that he crashed through a three thousand dollar interactive display about octopus intelligence. Tim's solution was to stand 15 feet away from the tank and throw food pellets like he was feeding pigeons at the park, which made Poseidon retreat to his cave and refuse to eat for two entire days. Then disaster struck on Wednesday evening when major marine research donors were arriving for a private feeding demonstration at 8:30, specifically to see our famous octopus interact with his primary caregiver. Twenty minutes before the VIP tour, Caroline cornered me in the equipment room while I prepared Poseidon's dinner of fresh dungeness crab and puzzle feeders. Tim will handle tonight's demonstration, she announced with fake authority dripping from every word. You're needed in the children's touch tank area for deep cleaning duties. Caroline snapped back that we'd manage without the feeding demonstration and gave me a direct order to report to the children's area immediately or face consequences. I slowly unclipped my security badge and identification card, placing both items On the stainless steel prep counter. While our senior aquarist and two night staff members watched this confrontation unfold in stunned silence, I pulled out my phone to start recording and told Caroline that the sighting was in full hunting mode because it was feeding time and Tim knew where all the equipment was stored. Caroline's face turned bright red when she realized I was documenting our conversation for legal. If you walk out of this building, you're terminated immediately and permanently. I replied calmly that this was perfectly fine with me, already hearing Poseidon's agitated flashing echoing from the deep sea exhibit rooms away. I'm recording this for unemployment documentation since you're firing me for refusing to endanger a four million dollar animal and potentially injure your completely inexperienced employee. I walked out of the building and barely made it to the parking lot before my phone started buzzing with frantic calls and text messages. Twelve missed calls came in during the first four minutes, starting with panicked messages from our senior Aquarius describing how Poseidon had grabbed Tim's entire arm through the feeding slot and refused to let go no matter.

voice_to_text: As a patient, what is the dumbest thing a doctor has ever recommended that you do? I was walking home from my friend's place around eleven PM when I heard this loud pop behind me, like someone slapping their hands together really hard. I felt something slam into my lower back and stumbled forward a few steps. My whole side went numb for a second. I turned around expecting to see some kid who threw a rock at me or something. Street was empty, just parked cars and dim streetlights. I reached back and touched where it hurt. No blood, just this weird tender spot near my hip. Felt like someone punched me really hard. So I kept walking. What else was I gonna do? Call the cops because my back hurt. I figured maybe a piece of metal fell off a truck or someone was shooting BB guns from their window. Happens in my neighborhood sometimes. The next morning I woke up and could barely roll over. The pain was way worse, like a constant throbbing that got sharper when I moved. I pressed on it and nearly jumped out of bed. Something was definitely wrong. My mom said I should go to urgent care. She dropped me off at this clinic near our house. The waiting room smelled like bleach and had those plastic chairs that stick to your legs. I sat there for like an hour watching some cooking show on the TV when they finally called Me back. This doctor barely looked at me. Young guy with messy hair who seemed like he'd rather be anywhere else. I told him what happened. He had me lift my shirt and just poked around the area for maybe 30 seconds. Probably just a bruise, he said. Already reaching for his prescription pad. Maybe pulled a muscle when you stumbled. These things happen. Just ignore it and it'll go away in a few days. I asked if he wanted to do an X ray or something. He actually laughed. For a bruise, that's a waste of time and money. Trust me, I've seen this 1,000 times. Take some ibuprofen and you'll be fine. So I left with a bottle of painkillers and this stupid feeling that he didn't take me seriously. The pain got worse that night, way worse. I couldn't sleep on my left side at all. Even sitting up in bed made me want to scream. My cousin Jerome came over the next day and saw me hobbling around like an old man. Dude, you look terrible. Something's really wrong. He kept bugging me to go to the hospital, the real hospital, not some urgent care place. By day 3, I gave in. The emergency room was packed, but they got me in pretty quick. When I described the pain, this nurse, older lady with kind eyes, actually listened. When I told her what happened. She nodded and said they needed to do some imaging. The X Ray tech was this chatty guy who kept cracking jokes while he positioned me on the table. Hold still now. Don't want any blurry pictures. He disappeared behind his lead wall and I heard the machine buzz. Then everything went quiet, way too quiet. The tech came back and stared at his computer screen for a long time. His smile was completely gone. Um, let me get the doctor. Three people rushed into the room. The er doctor looked at the screen and her face went white. Sir, when did you say?

voice_to_text: The kid who remained was angry and scared and disappearing into himself. By his 7th birthday, Liam had essentially stopped smiling. That's when I started lying to my wife about where I was going. Three nights a week, I told Nora I joined a grief support group for parents of disabled children. That wasn't technically untrue. I had joined one, attended twice, then stopped going because sitting in a circle talking about feelings wasn't going to help Liam hear music again. Then I started showing up at the university engineering lab where my old colleague Dennis worked on auditory research. I've been an audio engineer before kids and specialized in acoustic design and signal processing. Before work paid better, Dennis had access to equipment I couldn't afford and expertise I didn't have. And when I explained what I wanted to build, he looked at me like I'd lost my mind. A haptic vest that translates music into touch. That's not revolutionary. Those exist already, he said, pulling up commercial examples on his computer. They're crude. I they're basic vibration. I want something that can translate complex musical information that can let a deaf person experience a symphony with the same richness a hearing person does. Every instrument, every voice, every subtle dynamic change. I want my son to feel Beethoven the way Beethoven felt it when he was deaf. Dennis stared at me for a long moment, then said, that's probably impossible. Probably isn't definitely. I said, he's smiled when Can you start? For six months, I spent three nights a week in that lab while Nora thought I was at support group meetings. I'd come home at ten PM smelling like salt and coffee and she'd ask how the meeting was and I'd lie and say it was helpful, that sharing with other parents made me feel less alone. The guilt ate at me, but I couldn't tell her what I was really doing. Not until I knew it would work, not until I had something real to show her. Dennis and I built 17 prototypes. The first ones were disasters, just random buzzing that conveyed no meaningful information. Version 8 showed promise. We could distinguish between base and treble. Version 12 could separate three instruments. Version 15 could map an entire song with enough detail that when I wore it with my eyes closed, I could follow the melody through touch alone. It was extraordinary and terrifying, this feeling of music moving across my chest and back in waves and pulses and rhythms. And I'd stand there in the lab at midnight crying because Liam was going to be able to experience this, was going to get music back then. Version 15 caught fire during testing, literally caught fire, started smoking from a motor that overheated and I ripped it off my chest and watched six months of work burn in a metal trash can. While the smoke alarm screamed, Dennis stood there with a fire extinguisher looking Shaken, and I stood there watching smoke curl toward the ceiling, thinking this was over. I'd failed. There was no time to start again. But what happened next changed everything. Full story is linked below or on my channel.

voice_to_text: My son lost his hearing at age 6. Yesterday he put on headphones and cried. The fever spiked to 104 while Liam was singing in the bathtub. The er doctor took one look at his stiff neck and said the word that stops parents hearts, meningitis. What they didn't tell us in that moment, what we discovered six days later when Liam came home, was that the bacteria had already destroyed his cochlear nerve completely, irreversibly. At age 6, my son went from singing constantly to living in total silence. And the audiologist who delivered the diagnosis said there was nothing anyone could do. No hearing aids would help. No surgery could fix it. Liam was profoundly deaf and would be for the rest of his life. I watched him try to talk to his four year old sister Penny the day after we got the diagnosis, watched him yell, thinking he was speaking normally. Not broke like giving up, broke like the moment you realize you'll do anything, break any rule, spend any amount of time to fix what feels unfixable. Liam spiraled fast. He wasn't participating, wasn't socializing, seemed depressed in ways that terrified her. We tried sign language, but Liam hated it, would throw fits and cover his eyes so he didn't have to watch us gesture. He wanted his old life back and couldn't understand why we couldn't just make his ears work again. The worst part was watching him watch penny. Music had been his favorite thing. He'd sung constantly before the meningitis, made up songs about dinosaurs and trucks and whatever crossed his mind. Now all of that was gone.

voice_to_text: My husband fed me peanuts even though I am allergic, so I made him an amazing dinner as revenge. My husband is one of those people who believes that the power of the mind can combat anything. So much so that when my grandmother had cancer, he told her that instead of going to chemo, she should meditate and convince herself she isn't sick. I wouldn't mind it if he didn't push this ideology onto me, but he does, and our biggest problem has always been my peanut allergy. I am deathly allergic to peanuts and have been all my life, but he refuses to believe how severe it is and many times has tried forcing me to do exposure therapy. I even took him to the doctors with me, where he was told my allergy is so bad that exposure therapy could kill me. And still he claimed he was right and that the doctor was a brainwashed idiot. Well, yesterday he took it upon himself to prove that exposure therapy can work. I came home from work and he surprised me with a batch of homemade cookies. I was confused at first and asked him why he made them since he is lactose intolerant, but he said it was a surprise for me. I excitedly kissed him, but before taking a bite, I asked for the ingredients. He told me they were just normal cookies, then got me to smell one. I did and thought they smelled strange. But I didn't say anything. My husband then broke off an absolutely tiny piece and started inspecting it. He joked that he was just doing a quality check, then gave it to me. I ate the tiny piece and immediately started to feel hot. I broke into a sweat and my throat started to swell. I told my husband something was wrong, and when he saw me double over and grab my neck and chest, he called the ambulance. I went blue in the face and my body felt like it was on fire, but I mustered up the strength to yell at him to get the Epipen. He did as I asked and used it on me, and I instantly felt myself start to regain the ability to breathe. I heaved air into my lungs, and thankfully the ambulance came quickly. I was discharged after a few hours and was more or less okay. Afterwards, I asked my husband to explain how that happened.

voice_to_text: I taught my daughter to paint sunsets every evening for three years before learning she was completely colorblind. The art teacher's email arrived on a Wednesday afternoon with a subject line that made my stomach drop, concerns about Iris. Please call ASAP. Daughter was 7 years old and had been painting with me every single evening since she was 4, creating sunset after sunset with a skill that amazed everyone who saw her work. I called Missus Kellerman immediately from my office, already defensive before she even answered. Mister Cross, thank you for calling back so quickly, she said, her voice carefully neutral. I wanted to discuss something I noticed during today's art class. Iris completed a color wheel assignment and I'm concerned she might be having some vision issues. She paused and I heard papers rustling. She labeled every single color incorrectly, not just mixing up similar shades, but completely wrong identifications. She called red gray, orange, brown, yellow, light gray, green, medium gray. Every color on the wheel was mislabeled as some shade of gray. My first reaction was to defend Iris, to say the teacher must have misunderstood, but some something about the systematic nature of the errors stop me. I asked Missus Kellerman to email me photos of the assignment. And when they arrived five minutes later, I stared at my computer screen feeling like the floor was dissolving beneath my chair. The color wheel was technically perfect, each section painted with smooth gradients and precise Boundaries, but every label was wrong and exactly the way the teacher had described. I immediately thought about our painting sessions, the three years of evening rituals where we painted hundreds of sunsets together. And suddenly I was seeing them differently. How many times had I said mix orange and pink for those clouds? And watched Iris confidently select paints while I praised her color choices? I left work early and drove home in a daze, calling Iris's pediatrician from the car. Doctor Patel squeezed us in for an appointment the next morning and referred us to a pediatric ophthalmologist named Doctor Vivian Leeds, who specialized in color vision deficiencies. I watched Iris during our painting session with new attention, really looking at what she was doing. We were painting the sunset visible through our dining room window, and I described it out loud the way I always did. Look at those beautiful orange and pink clouds, I said, pointing at the sky. Try mixing some cadmium orange with a touch of titanium white and maybe a hint of quinacridone magenta. Iris nodded seriously and reached for paints, confidently squeezing colors onto her palette. But when I looked closely at what she'd selected, my chest tightened. The orange she'd chosen was actually a brown. The pink was a gray. She was mixing them together with complete confidence, creating a muddy, brownish gray mixture.

voice_to_text: What's the worst thing someone told you after you recovered from a coma? I woke up in a hospital bed after eight weeks, and the first words out of my brother's mouth were, we had to put Cooper down. I'm sorry. He wouldn't eat that. Said it was kinder this way. Cooper was my six year old golden retriever. I'd raised him from a puppy. He slept at the foot of my bed every single night. When I tried to speak, nothing came out except his choking sound. My brother patted my shoulder and said, it's okay. We got the kids a new puppy, a Labrador. They named him Buddy. They were talking about replacing my dog like he was a broken appliance. My name is Tim, short for Timothy. And before the accident, I was a software engineer living alone with Cooper. Denver. The accident happened when a delivery truck ran a red light and T boned my car at 50 miles per hour. The impact threw me into a concrete barrier, and I sustained severe head trauma that required emergency surgery. I've been in a medically induced coma for three weeks and then in a minimally conscious state for another five weeks. During that entire time, I could hear everything happening around me, but my body wouldn't respond. I couldn't move or speak or signal that I was conscious and understanding every word. What my family didn't know was that my brain was recording every conversation with perfect Clarity. I have this thing where I remember details really well. Always have. After the head injury, that ability got even stronger. Every word spoken near my hospital bed got stored in my mind with exact precision. My mom visited during the first month talking about medical bills piling up. Mentioned Cooper a few times saying my brother was taking care of him. Then around week 4, her tone changed. She stopped mentioning Cooper. Instead, she talked about how my brother's kids wanted a puppy and how expensive coop first food and vet bills were. She said we might need to make some practical decisions about the dog. My brother visited less, but when he did, he talked to my mom in the hallway. I could hear every word he said. Cooper was getting depressed, wouldn't eat much, just sat by the front door waiting. My mom said, we can't keep spending money on a dog when your kids want one and Tim might not even wake up. maybe it would be kinder to put him down before he suffers more. I was screaming inside.

voice_to_text: What's the smartest way you tested which family members actually loved you? I pretended to get arrested to see who would bail me out. Three months ago, I got the idea after watching my cousin get locked up for a bar fight and his parents had him out in under an hour. Meanwhile, I've been the family a t m for years, covering my sister's car payment four months straight, putting down 12,000 for my brother's condo and lending my uncle eight grand for his landscaping business. So when I needed help moving last September from a third floor walk up, nobody could make it. My sister had brunch, my brother had work, my uncle's back hurt. So I started planning my revenge. I called my buddy who works at the precinct and he agreed to stage a fake arrest at our family barbecue last Sunday. He showed up in uniform with a patrol car, read me my rights in front of everyone and cuffed me next to the grill where my dad was cooking burgers. Charged with destruction of property at a local business and bail was set at $5,000, which I'd casually mentioned the week before at dinner that I had sitting in my savings account from my work bonus. My sister was the first person to react. She pulled out her phone immediately and started recording vertical video for social media. This is going straight to TikTok, she said, actually laughing out loud like it was the Funniest thing she'd ever witnessed. My brother walked inside the house to grab another beer from the fridge. Absolutely nothing was happening. Didn't even bother to ask what I supposedly destroyed or if I was okay. My uncle, the exact one whose entire landscaping business I funded with my own money, said, well, you shouldn't have broken the law, buddy, and casually flipped his burger on the grill. My mom was more worried about what the neighbours would think. She told me I'd embarrass the whole family in front of everyone on the street. My dad said, this is exactly what happens when you don't think before acting. He refused to even look at me, just kept grilling like I wasn't being arrested 10 feet away from him. Then about five minutes later, my girlfriend pulled up in her car. She wasn't even invited to the Barbie. Someone from my family had texted her about what was happening. And she drove straight over, still wearing her work scrubs from her hospital shift. She came running up to the patrol car with this panicked look on her face asking if I was okay, what happened? Are you hurt? How much is the bail? And when my buddy who was playing the officer said $5,000, she didn't even hesitate.

John provocatively made the hand gesture. Bruno immediately responded. John grinned triumphantly. The man, seeing this, lost control. He frantically mimicked John's gesture, trying to command his own dog, but his dog just stood frozen in place. Just then, the light turned green. You have a nice day now, Angie, roll over. Roll over, Angie. A satisfied John jog down the street, unaware of a figure closing in behind him. Suddenly, a car slammed to a halt before him. A cloth was pressed over his nose and mouth, releasing the acrid smell of burning plastic. As John was about to pass out, he Saw Bruno being dragged into the car. When John slowly regained consciousness in the biting cold wind, only one thought filled his mind. Whoever had kidnapped Bruno, he would find them.

voice_to_text: I heated a wire until it was red hot, hammered it into a sharp spike, and while the guy slept, I quietly slipped off his swim goggles. Then I jumped into the sea to spear fish, thinking everything was under control. Little did I know this moment would make me regret it for the rest of my life. When the guy woke up and found his goggles gone, he flew into a rage and grabbed a spear ready to sink me. My wife grabbed the spear to stop him, but she was too weak. She couldn't hold it and even tore her clothes in the struggle. Seeing that, the guy didn't hesitate when I came back full of fish and tossed the goggles to him, he should have been angry, but instead he seemed oddly pleased. I felt something was off, but I didn't think too much of it and proudly showed off my prize, just wanting to fill my stomach. Then I noticed my wife's eyes darting away and my chest tightened. He didn't say a word, and I started to realize the seriousness of the situation. I looked back at the guy next door and suddenly understood. Rage surged through me. I grabbed her and threw her in front of the guy, hoping she'd repent. But minutes later, to my shock, she and the guy were chillingly dancing together like nothing had happened. Seeing that, I turned green with anger. I couldn't stand it. I swore to myself. They'd pay for this. So I smashed a glass bottle, ground down the bottom, glued it to the neck, softened a plastic bottle over a flame, cut it open and sealed the mouth with black rubber, made a makeshift diving mask. I couldn't wait and dove in. Underwater was clearer than I expected. Excited, I planned to spear a few big fish to spite them. But then I spotted a sunken dinghy. It only had a small hole. Fixable. My mind lit up. Repair that boat and I could get off this island. I abandoned the fishing idea, took off the goggles and started hauling the boat. Walking in water is brutal. Pulling a boat heavier than me nearly exhausted me. I gasped for air, kept going, terrified the tide would wash it away. Finally, I dragged the dinghy up onto shore. The I saw it and seemed to realize this might be our way out. He ran over to help, but I barked at him to stop. He'd humiliated me before. Now he had the nerve to cozy up to me. No way. For days I worked on the boat dreaming of leaving the island. Then my wife came to apologize saying she did what she did to survive and begging me to take her when the boat was ready. I wasn't stupid. I didn't buy her one sided excuse and turned away in anger. Not long after, the boat was fixed and even had a sale seeing the Guy busy. I grabbed my spear, planning to catch a few more fish for provisions. But as soon as I hit the water, I sensed something was wrong. I surfaced and saw they had already loaded all their stuff into the dinghy. They were trying to steal my boat. Fury boiled over. I sprinted to the shore, trying to stop them, but it was too late. They'd pushed the boat into the water. I chased after them but couldn't catch up and could only roar on the beach watching them sail away. My anger strangely shifted to amusement. I lay back in my chair, ready to watch the show.

voice_to_text: This woman took off her top just wanting to enjoy a swim. But as soon as she surfaced, she saw a hundred dollar Bill floating on the water. Lisa couldn't believe it. She slowly moved closer and snatched the cash. But then she saw something even crazier. There were more hundred dollar bills up ahead. She was ecstatic. As she gathered the money, she looked around and spotted four black bags on the shore. Lisa's eyes lit up. Could they be full of money? She rushed over and unzipped one just to crack to see. The look on her face said it all. At a glance, it looked like 2 million per bag, a whopping $8 million total. She couldn't believe her luck. Not wanting her friends to find out, she quickly got dressed, planning to sneak the bags away in her kayak. Just then, her friend Leo popped out of nowhere asking where she was going. Feeling caught, Lisa had to spill the beans. He promised him a split and they were instantly on the same page. But just as they were about to leave, their third friend, Jack, walked up, seeing they were about to ditch him. Jack was pissed, so Lisa told him about the money and offered him a cut, too. But Jack wasn't having it. I'm not ruining my life for some dirty money, he said. He warned them to be careful, then took a cloth strip from one of the bags, tied it to his torn Backpack and walked off alone. Lisa and Leo didn't waste any time. They loaded the money into the kayak and started paddling toward town. But they hadn't gone far when they saw a bunch of tourists on the shore with two cops standing right there. Lisa panicked. Before she could even catch her breath, another tourist paddled right past them. A little later, they pulled over on a deserted shore to rest and Lisa made a shocking discovery. One of the four bags was gone. They were both stunned. They tied them together with a dead knot. How could one just vanish? Did they leave it back there? Lisa quickly called Jack and asked him to go take a look. But by now, Jack was already in trouble. He'd run into a stranger on the trail who turned out to be the owner of the money. Turns out a day earlier, a guy named Paul was making a getaway with a stash of cash in his plane. The plane malfunctioned, so he had to toss the money out and parachute down to find it. He'd been searching for a day and a night with no luck. But now he finally saw the yellow strap on the bag, the special marker he'd used. Paul recognized it instantly. Luckily, Jack was sharp. He knew that out here in the deep woods, this guy was bad news. So he just bolted. Paul was right on his heels. Jack was terrified to lighten his Load. He ripped off his backpack and threw it on the ground. And that's when the unthinkable happened.

voice_to_text: This woman was raped by a delivery man. But after the rapist was imprisoned, she made a decision that no one could understand. She wrote to the rapist asking to visit him in prison. However, the letter was rejected and returned. Seeing the unclaimed stamp on the letter, Miranda didn't give up. If the first letter wasn't received, she'd send a second one. If the second wasn't received, she would keep writing. She persisted, and eventually, after hundreds of rejected letters, the rapist finally accepted one of her letters and agreed to meet her in prison. The letter that was returned included the words, you win. It seemed that he was moved by her persistence. A year after the incident, Miranda finally met the man who violated her. She faced the man who had caused her so much pain. The man thought she had come to accuse him so he couldn't look her in the eye and kept apologizing. But what he didn't expect was that Miranda wasn't there to scold him. Instead, she asked him how life was in prison, like a wife concerned about her husband. This confused the man. What happened next was even more shocking. Miranda visited him every week, and each time she looked more attractive and sexy. They began talking about daily life in the past, and their relationship grew more and more ambiguous. The man never imagined that the victim would fall in love with him. He, being naive, soon fell in love. With Miranda as well. He promised he would reform in prison and try to get out early to make up for his past mistakes, to get out sooner. Even if he was bullied by other prisoners, he wouldn't fight back. What he didn't know was every time Miranda heard that he was being bullied in prison, she appeared worried. But deep down she felt a strange sense of pleasure. One day, the man told Miranda that he had been granted Parole and would soon be released from prison. Upon hearing this, Miranda was stunned. She never thought that a rapist could be released so soon. The man who ruined her life would receive so little punishment. She forced herself to smile and acted happy for him. She couldn't reveal any sign of weakness because her plan was just beginning.

After removing the front fuse, he cut open the hostages clothes and successfully cut the rear fuse as well. The morning light went out. The silly asked the hostage to let go of the controller in his hand. But out of fear the hostage's hand wouldn't obey him, the silly slowly helped him put down the controller. Just when they thought they had accomplished their mission, the silly noticed that the timer behind him had not stopped. It turned out to be an impossible bomb. Silly held the bomb and let the hostage escape slowly. The hostage was so scared that he fled forward quickly. The silly held the bomb like this, his heart undisturbed, quietly waiting for that moment to come.

voice_to_text: Because he had an affair with his friend's wife, he was locked in a secret room by his friend. The hammer couldn't break open the iron door. The man carefully examined the oxygen cylinders in the cabinet. He used a wrench to open the valve at the bottom of the oxygen cylinder and tried to turn on the switch. To his surprise, there was still plenty of oxygen in the cylinder. This gave him hope. He immediately grabbed other parts and began assembling them. Before long, a complete set of oxyacetylene welding tools was assembled. Looking at the flames spurting from the welding torch, he thought he would definitely be able to open the door. But after the man used the oxyacetylene torch for a long time, the sturdy iron door only had its surface blackened. The steel inside hadn't melted at all. He took off his protective goggles and angrily grabbed the hammer. Charging at the cabinet, he smashed and kicked it to vent his emotions. After venting, the man slumped down by the door, falling into deep despair. He had been trapped here for three days now. His friend had never shown up. He could only wait here to die. Just then, he suddenly discovered a small hole in the smooth wall. Hope instantly ignited. He took off his shirt and hurriedly grabbed the hammer and chisel, making one last struggle. Unexpectedly, the seemingly thick concrete wall was much softer than he had imagined. In no time, the Small hole was smashed into a large hole. The man's heart was filled with wild joy. The speed of chiseling the wall became faster and faster. It looked like he would soon chisel through the wall and escape through the hole. At this moment, the rotten, stinking, dead rat in the room finally came in handy. The man picked up maggots from the rat's body, holding them in his hand like peanuts, then slap them into his mouth in one go. This provided precious energy for his body. After filling his stomach, he had more strength to chisel the wall. Soon he chiseled through the concrete and the rebar inside was exposed. Fortunately, these rebars were very thin and weren't really a problem. The man lit the oxygen acetylene torch and before long he had burned through all the rebars. Over the next two days, he endured hunger, sleeping when tired, and chiseling the wall when awake. With perseverance beyond ordinary imagination, he finally succeeded in chiseling through the wall. Looking at the light coming through the hole in the wall, the man was too excited to speak. He swung the hammer as fast as he could to make the hole bigger, then crawled out on all fours with wild joy. But the moment the man crawled out of the hole, the despair swallowed him again. Outside was another sealed room.

voice_to_text: A blind woman removed her diamond necklace before bathing when a thief appeared outside the bathroom. After her shower, she opened the door to find the thief holding a towel for her with a dagger. She wrapped herself in the towel and stepped out, the thief staring at her. She stumbled in the dining room and realized a stranger was in her home. She immediately turned and fled into the bedroom, slamming the door shut. She turned on her computer and used voice recognition to send a distress signal. The thief smashed the window with a chair and broke into the bedroom. She turned and fled toward the door, feeling her way along the wall until she reached the stairwell. The thief caught up in the stairwell. She was already running swiftly toward the first floor, feeling the railing. The thief pursued relentlessly behind her. She escaped to the ground floor, feeling her way along the safety netting until she reached the main street. She pleaded for help from passers by on the street. A man approached, showed his credentials to the crowd and began calming her. Seeing this, the thief had no choice but to temporarily abandon the chase. The man called for backup, then escorted her back to the apartment lobby. The thief entered through a side door, ushered her into the elevator. They were in cahoots all along. They returned to her apartment, demanding to know where her boyfriend had hidden the diamonds he'd embezzled. But she Knew nothing, she turned and fled to the rooftop terrace. The man approached and ripped the diamond necklace from her neck. Faced with interrogation, she changed tactics. First, she LED the thief to search the refrigerator in the dining room. Then she guided the man to inspect the potted plants on the terrace. The thief immediately sensed something was amiss. He picked up an ice cube. The diamond was inside. The man smashed every planter, finding no diamonds. The thief melted all the ice cubes with water, retrieving every diamond. He turned to see his accomplice stuffing items into his pockets. Thus, the two thieves turned on each other. After both suffered losses, she skillfully refroze the diamonds in water and hid them back in the refrigerator.

voice_to_text: That night was my wedding night. I smiled at him, but his face turned cold in an instant. What's so funny? Nothing. His movements were stiff and lifeless, without a trace of love. Worse than the wedding bed was the house he chose for us. And small and dull inside. The moment we stepped in, he started giving orders. He said I had to cook and clean every day. He warned me never to step into his study. He said he once published a textbook, that it made him a lot of money, and now he was working on a second one. I believed he was truly talented. When I offered to help organize his notes. Entirely unnecessary. To write, a man needs the three p's. Not now. Pencil, paper and peace. He refused immediately. He took me to the bedroom. He told me to learn how to iron his shirts. After seeing him off each morning, I was left with endless chores. It felt like being trapped in a cage. One day, I passed by a tennis court. I signed up for a class on a whim. That night at dinner, I told him about it. His face darkened instantly. Can I tell you that I've already spent all of my money on you? I bought you an entire house. I had no idea what I did wrong. He came home late that night without a single word of apology. He just went through the motions of being a Husband. A few days later, two men came knocking. They said my husband owed them a large sum of money. The house was about to be taken away. I told them he was about to release a new book, that it could cover the debt. Mr. Elephant has referenced the hordes of gold he made from his last textbook. Only trouble was, when we looked into it, it doesn't exist. It was never published. I rushed into the study. His so called manuscripts were nothing but meaningless papers. He had been lying from the very start. I packed my things in a hurry, ready to leave. Just as I reached the door, he came back. He grabbed my suitcase. I shouted, calling him a fraud. He snapped in anger and dragged me back inside. When I opened my eyes again, I had no idea how long had passed. I escaped the house and cleaned my wounds at a sink. People on the street just stared coldly. With nowhere else to go, I could only turn to my aunt for help.

voice_to_text: I turned the prisoners into a human centipede. Their mouths were connected to others buttocks. The length could even circle an entire soccer field. Not only did it save food, it was also more convenient for management. When the prisoners had served their full sentences and were released, there would be no abnormalities on their bodies, only some scars on their mouths. To ensure the body modifications went smoothly, I especially recruited a highly skilled surgeon. I anesthetized all the prisoners with a tranquillizer gun. At my command, the prisoners were taken into the operating room. Seeing my plan proceed smoothly, I danced for joy. As time passed, the surgeries also began to go smoothly. But a few prisoners had poor digestive systems and frequently had diarrhea. If they were placed in the middle, the people behind them would starve to death. To ensure the plan was foolproof, I directly killed those prisoners on the spot. That day, the governor came down to inspect. I took the governor to see my great masterpiece, a human centipede of over 100 people laid out right before us. This horrifying scene even left the governor in awe. To ensure the food supply has specifically placed the big fat man weighing 200 gin at the very front. Starting from what the first person ate, it cycled all the way to the last person. All of this was only the beginning because I had another version. This version was specially designed for death row inmates. Those prisoners had their hands and feet hacked off and were then connected together. I had expected the governor to praise me, but the governor actually yelled that I was inhumane. This dealt a severe blow to me emotionally. The surgeon responsible for the operation burst in, about to brag about his perfect masterpiece. Now, knowing I was in a rage, I killed him on the spot. I then pointed the gun at the secretary. Just as I was about to pull the trigger, the governor suddenly turned back. He changed his mind, thinking this was a very good method. I was overjoyed. I hugged the secretary. But the next second, I still picked up the handgun.

voice_to_text: The man walked into the mall. He was shocked to find countless hellish phantoms crawling all over the mall. What was even more eerie, the people around couldn't see these monsters at all. They still chatted and laughed as if nothing was wrong. Only Thomas was extremely anxious, for he knew clearly that the appearance of these monsters, it meant a massacre would soon befall the entire mall. Suddenly, a scream came from a distance. A gun, he's gotta go. Everyone was instantly scared and fled in all directions, but the mall's doors were locked shut. At that moment, Thomas ran into the mall against the crowd. Sure enough, he saw a gangster reloading an M16. Then the gangster fired wildly at the surrounding people. He noticed his girlfriend was within the gangster's firing range. Thomas immediately pulled out his pistol, rushed forward to take down the gangster, but his shooting skills were too poor. Every shot missed the gangster by a hair. At the same time, those monsters suddenly surrounded him, trying to stop Thomas. At this life or death moment, Thomas broke free and shot the gangster dead with one bullet. After that, he walked tremblingly toward his girlfriend. The place was in a mess. The walls were covered with bullet holes. It wasn't until his girlfriend stood up safely that the two of them cried tears of joy. Suddenly, another phantom appeared out of nowhere. A woman across from him shouted for help. He realized the danger. Wasn't fully over yet, so he quickly followed the woman. Only then did he realize that this woman was the soul of someone who had just died. She LED the man to the basement and then disappeared. The man instantly realized that the real danger was hidden in this car. After he and the driver saw the car open, both of them started trembling with fear. Immediately, time was running out fast. A phantom suddenly appeared behind them. It looked at the policeman in the distance, then drilled into his body. The policeman seemed to be controlled by it. The driver shouted for everyone to leave the scene quickly, but it was already too late.

voice_to_text: A billionaire worth billions lost half his fortune over one petty move. He yanked his arm and the girl's bracelet snapped in half. She yelled that he went too far, but the man didn't apologize. Instead, he took out 2 yuan and handed it to her. The humiliation made her shake with anger. But what could a poor girl do to pay for college? She took on every job she could find, even working as a nanny for the rich. One day, while she was cleaning, a strange man walked into the house. She hid in the corner, terrified the and heard the noise and the two chased each other around the room until they bumped straight into each other. The billionaire instantly recognized her, the waitress who had talked back to him. Facing this tall, intimidating man, the girl begged him not to hurt her. Only when he said he was the homeowner did she finally calm down. He quickly explained she was the new cook and cleaner. The man looked puzzled but said she could stay as long as she stayed out of sight whenever he was home. Later, she told her best friend what happened. Her friend looked him up online and gasped. He wasn't just a billionaire, he was also single. The next day, she was busy in the kitchen again when a little boy suddenly appeared and scared her. He was the billionaire's nephew. The boy was playful and sweet and soon the two became Friends. They had a pillow fight, feathers flying everywhere, and even dragged the sofa outside to build a tent. When the billionaire came home, he found the house a total mess. He scolded her on the spot. The little boy ran to comfort her. Though uncle has a fiery temper, he's actually a really good person. Tears still glistened in the girl's eyes. Soon after, the billionaire told her to make dinner. She served a cheese salad, but he frowned and asked, who told you to change the menu? The boy jumped in and said, it's my favorite dish. The man sighed and didn't argue further. The boy begged his uncle to let her eat with them. She tried to refuse, saying she was working. But the billionaire, out of politeness, invited her to join. After dinner, the three sat in the yard watching a movie, laughing and playing a popcorn throwing game. Before going to the bathroom, the boy whispered to his uncle, don't bully her while I'm gone. Then he turned back again just to make sure the girl laughed, calling him adorable. The man said quietly, I was like that when I was a kid, she teased. Hard to believe you were ever cute. After she returns home, her best friend had gone to a bar, a bar known for trapping rich men. She rushed there with another friend and saw her bestie surrounded by drunk old guys. She stormed in, yelled at the men and dragged Her friend out. But that scene was witnessed by the wealthy man's friend. A friend relayed the incident to the wealthy man, leading him to mistakenly believe that the family's maid had designs on him.

voice_to_text: Just because I threw away my student's phone, he took revenge and killed my daughter. I am a biology teacher. My daughter is in my class. One day I found that a boy in my class had sent her an adult video. I was furious and threw his phone out the window. Maybe he felt humiliated because the way he looked at me was full of hate. A few days later, on Valentine's Day, my daughter dressed up and went to a bar with her friends. It was getting late and she still hadn't come back. So I called her. She said she would be home in half an hour. And I felt a little relieved. But what I didn't know was that after hanging up, she was kidnapped by strangers. I waited for a long time, but she never came back. I couldn't reach her on the phone. So I went to the police station in panic to file a report. But the police didn't seem concerned at all. Seeing that the police did nothing, I had no choice but to go to the bar myself, but I still couldn't find her. The next day when I saw her again, she was barely alive. Over one night, my beautiful, innocent girl had become unrecognizable. What was even harder for me to accept was when the doctor told me, replay 1, what it means for a girl to be raped in India. As a mother, I understood it all too well. I called my husband in tears. My daughter survived and with courage beyond her ears, recorded a statement. The boys involved were arrested the same day. That arrest came the beginning of a different fight. My daughter testified on video in court, stripping herself of dignity to speak the truth while powerful forces moved behind the scenes. The judge was compromised and dismissed her testimony on the basis that she had been drunk that night. The four boys hired a formidable lawyer and after 38 days of legal battle, they were declared not guilty for lack of evidence. The verdict was a calculated injustice. My husband lost control and struck one of the boys in court. He was detained for assault. My mind went blank. My daughter remained in that bed, fragile, while the men responsible returned to their families as if nothing had happened. I'm so sorry about what has happened. When I saw one of those boys at school the next day, he carried himself with the arrogance of someone untouchable. Watching him thinking of my daughter and of the system that failed us, and I knew what I had to do. I decided to take revenge myself.

I curiously asked my daughter about it. She told me it was a secret. Having no other choice, I could only go ask the nanny. Her reply was very natural, but her eyes deliberately avoided mine. I started to suspect her, but I had no evidence. I could only buy a hidden camera to monitor her and my daughter's every moment. Time came to the day of my daughter's performance. I never could. After returning home, I still decided to fire her. Why did you fire her? She was my best friend. I hate you. When my daughter heard the news, she lost control of her emotions and rushed upstairs. That night, I suddenly realized my daughter was missing. I frantically called the police. The police, however, told me the nanny had no birth records in the hospital's archives. She was only recorded as a Newborn abandoned by her parents. What hospital? Saint Anthony's in Wakefield. I stood frozen in place. I had abandoned a child there. It was a mistake I made when I was young. Realizing the severity of the situation, I rushed home and checked the surveillance footage. On the camera, I saw the nanny crawling out from under my daughter's bed. If you ever want To see your precious daughter again. You'll meet me at your husband's construction site. No police, no Mark, just you.

Having just moved into their new home, the two were totally creeped out and thought they'd gotten the worst luck. Little did they know this was only the beginning. The next day, Teddy checked the news and found out the guy who died the night before was a young football player. There was a hidden curve right by their driveway and he couldn't hit the brakes in time, which cost him his life. Teddy felt really bad for the guy, but since the crash happened right outside his house, he figured he had a responsibility to do something about it. So he took a close look at that curve and noticed tons of old, worn skid marks on the pavement. Clearly, this wasn't the first accident there. To keep another tragedy from happening, Teddy used the lawn mower to clear out all the weeds along the road, making the warning sign that been hidden in the grass much more visible. Every night when he had nothing to do, he'd sit in the yard and keep a close eye on the road. But even that wasn't enough to stop another accident. One day, Teddy was grilling in the backyard when he heard a loud crash. He ran over and saw another Car had been in a terrible wreck. The driver still had a pulse, but Teddy had no clue how to perform first aid. By the time the police and ambulance arrived, the driver had already passed away. Teddy was consumed with guilt, blaming himself for not knowing any first aid skills, for letting the guy die right in front of him. He poured out his heartache to Brooke, saying if he'd been able to give the driver CPR right away, maybe he would have survived. But Brooke couldn't handle it anymore. She insisted they had to move out within a week. With accidents happening one after another, she thought the house was cursed. No wonder the previous owner had sold it at an absurdly low price. On top of that, their son kept saying he could smell a rotten stench in the house. Brooke was convinced it meant way too many tragedies had happened there and kids could pick up on that bloody stench. But Teddy refused to move. He was dead set on staying, determined to put an end to the tragedies once and for all.

voice_to_text: Every day, my mom puts 100 pound barbell into my backpack before leaving. She also hangs two sandbags around my neck. She doesn't do this to train my body. She does it to keep my secret from being discovered. Because ever since I was little, I've had a superpower no one else has. My body floats into the air whenever my emotions fluctuate. Since I can't control this power, my mom always keeps me by her side. Whenever she sees me start to float, she immediately pulls me back down. But having a power like this is dangerous, so we've been forced to live a secluded life. As time passed, I grew up, but I still couldn't control this ability. Whenever I saw a girl I liked, my feet would lift off the ground. I tried to calm myself down, but the bus suddenly jolted. I slammed into the window. The pain instantly broke my concentration, and my feet slowly returned to the floor. I thought it was just a random accident, but I didn't expect the new transfer student in class to be that same girl from the bus. When she greeted me, my calm heart started to race again. I gripped the desk tightly, muttering digits of pie under my breath. I didn't relax until everyone had left the classroom. But Anna hadn't gone far. Her clothes were soaked from the rain, and I couldn't take my eyes off her. I quickly grabbed a nearby railing, afraid my Secret would be exposed. But Anna didn't notice. She just walked past me with her backpack. The next morning, Anna barely brushed against me, and I shot straight into the air. She looked surprised, but class was about to start, so she didn't think much of it. However, she noticed the wound on my hand. After school, she came up to me and gently applied ointment to my hand. From then on, we started getting closer. We ate together and went to school together. My mom made pork cutlets. Her dad sold fried chicken. We had more and more to talk about. One day, Anna asked for my help. She had to do 100 sit UPS in under a minute. But being that close to her made my body float again. This time, I flew right over Anna's head. She was about to ask why that happened, but the janitor rushed in and kicked us out. After that, Anna couldn't stop thinking about it, so she decided to follow me. She traced my footprints to the school building. But when she reached the crossroads, the footprints suddenly disappeared.

voice_to_text: I was always the top student in my school, but during the college entrance exam, I couldn't even move my pen because in every test before, Tony had always helped me answer the questions. But that day, Tony got stuck in traffic. Looking at my incomplete hands, I suddenly felt completely helpless. I didn't want my three years of hard work to go to waste. So I tried to flip open the paper with my mouth and bite the pen just to write my name. But no matter how hard I tried, I just couldn't do it. When the exam ended, I was filled with despair. In a fit of hopelessness, I went straight to the rooftop. At that moment, I wanted to end my miserable life, because before the exam even started, when Tony still hadn't shown up, I tried asking strangers passing by for help, but not a single person was willing to lend a hand. In the end, I placed my last hope on the Proctor. But to my shock, even the teacher gave up on me. Now I no longer have the right to blame anyone. What made it worse was that the minister of the Interior's daughter decided to go shopping that day, so she used her father's power to block off the roads, which accidentally trapped Tony halfway. By the time Tony finally reached school, it was already too late. As he rushed desperately toward the rooftop, he heard the screams of the crowd. Below because I had chosen to end my life in this. Tony was devastated. At the same time, my brother also arrived. He had gotten my message asking for help, but he, too, was stuck in traffic. He had even asked a police officer by the roadside for help, but the officer's response left him heartbroken. And just like that, death separated me and my brother forever.
