voice_to_text: My face is covered in sand, but I dare not wipe it off. Behind me is a sheer cliff. A fall would mean certain death. I grit my teeth, frowning, concentrating all my strength on my index finger, clutching the sand, not daring to move a muscle. But the sand is too soft. It can't support my weight. And soon I begin to slide. Panic. I quickly come up with an idea, spreading my legs wide, pressing my head to the ground for more friction, barely managing to stop myself. Just then, my phone rings from my backpack. The chance to call for help is right in front of me. I cautiously raise my right hand, but before I can reach my phone, my body slides down a lot more. I tremble, press flat to the ground. But I won't give up the chance to survive. After a moment of hesitation, I steady my breathing carefully, raise my left hand, reach for the backpack and slowly unzip it. Just as I'm about to grab the phone, I lose my balance, sliding quickly downward, I forced my arms and legs against the cliff and narrowly saved myself. Now I have nowhere to go. Above me, soft sand, below, high rocks. One wrong move and I'm dead for sure. Fear and helplessness spread through my body. Suddenly, an idea hits me. I begin to calculate the intervals between waves hitting the rocks. After a few checks, I find the right moment. I Turn around. I don't die from the fall, but the water is too shallow. My weight slams into a rock. Pain surges through me and I lose consciousness. Luckily, I regain awareness, quickly swim back to the surface and climb up the nearest rock. I've made it just barely. I'm overjoyed. My tense nerve is finally relaxing. But then I feel a sharp pain in my palm and realize my hand has been cut with a 10 centimeter long gash. It's a shocking sight, too gruesome to look at, but at least I'm still alive. After studying myself, I prepare to leave. But the moment I take a step, I crash hard onto the rocks and pass out. I don't know how long it's been, but the waves wake me. I try to move, but my legs are paralyzed. During the fall, my pelvis was crushed by the rocks and I'm slowly losing feeling in my feet. Then I remember my phone, but it's been ruined by the seawater, totally useless. I look helplessly at the sky calling out, but in this deserted sea, there's no response. I take off my shirt, bandage the wound and look around, searching for a way out. In the distance, an island is my only hope. I decide to take a chance, grab my bag and struggle toward the rocks. One quick roll, I dive back into the sea, dragging my half paralyzed body, using one arm to swim with all my might. Halfway There I feel a sharp pain in my abdomen, and suddenly I disappear below the surface. I instinctively scream, but my voice is lost in bubbles. Survival instincts keep me fighting, and finally, I break the surface again, but I'm exhausted, and the lack of oxygen knocks me out. This time, I have no strength left to fight. My body sinks slowly. My feet touch the seafloor.

voice_to_text: Carrie was the only one who did not cooperate with the detectives and decided to go to trial. And this is where she was found guilty of Irene's murder and the jury actually recommended the death sentence. She is currently 65 years old and is serving her death sentence at the Central California Women's Facility. And because she's in California, I don't think we will ever see her be executed. The last person I wanna talk about today is 55 year old Veronica Gonzales who has been serving a death sentence in California for the last 27 years. She was sentenced to death for the absolutely horrific torture and murder of her 4 year old niece Jenny Rohas. When I say absolutely horrific, some of the details of what they did to this little girl are by far the worst things that I have ever, ever read. I'm not going to go into exact details of what they did to her, not only because it's extremely graphic, but also because I don't even think there's time to talk about everything that they did to this girl. In 1995, four year old Jenny Rohas began living with her aunt and uncle Veronica and Ivan Gonzales. And this was after her mother had lost custody of her. Six other children also lived in this home with them. And the home was in absolutely deplorable conditions. There were cockroaches everywhere. There was no food in the house. None of the children had beds And all of the children had lice. While Jenny was living there, Veronica and Ivan began very brutally torturing and abusing her. She was frequently beaten, strangled, handcuffed and starved. They would burn her with a blow dryer or curling iron, burn her with boiling hot water, handcuff her and force her to sleep in a box. Just absolutely horrific, horrific things. On July 21st of 1995, they both forcefully submerged Jenny into a bathtub full of scalding hot water. Water temperature was 156 degrees Fahrenheit and was so extremely hot that it peeled the skin and the toenails off of the lower half of her body. She had severe burns to over 50% of her body to the point where several parts of her body was missing skin and she was even missing hair from her head. And I really want you to think about what I just said because after this happened, Veronica and Ivan let her sit there and suffer for six hours until she eventually stopped breathing and she died. When Jenny was brought to the hospital, they discovered that she had injuries to every single part of her body and they were in various stages of healing. So she had been abused for a while. There were so many injuries to this little 4 year old's body that it took up 10 pages of the court documents to just describe her injuries. Veronica and Ivan were immediately arrested following Jenny's death and they both went to Trial where they were found guilty of her murder and they were both sentenced to death. Ivan is currently 58 years old and is serving his death sentence at the California State Prison. Veronica is currently 55 years old and is serving her death sentence at the Central California Women's Facility and because she's in California I don't think we will ever see her be executed. I'm going to go ahead and end it there for time sake but please let me know if you guys want me to keep this series going and go over some more of the women on this list. Also please let me know if you guys like how I'm currently doing this. Right now I'm doing 3 women at a time because I like to give a little bit of details on the case but if you'd rather see a much more quicker breakdown so that I can cover more women in a video please let me know and I can try to change it up. But anyways, thanks for watching and I'll see you in the next video.

voice_to_text: Did you know there are currently 2,100 men on death row but only 48 women? Let's do another video where we talk about some of these women that are on death row and what exactly they did to get there. Really quickly before I begin, all three of the women I'm talking about today are from California. And death row in California has been dismantled. So that means that all three of these women are still serving a death sentence. However, they are no longer on death row and they're just in general population in prison. The first person I want to talk about today is 63 year old Cynthia Kaufman who has been serving a death sentence in California for the last 35 years. And she was actually the very first woman to receive the death penalty in California since it was reinstated back in 1977. She was sentenced to death after her and her boyfriend kidnapped and murdered four different women over the span of two months back in 1986. Cynthia began dating a man who had just been released from jail by the name of James Marlowe. Quickly after they began dating, they began using drugs, they got married and then they started to commit very violent crimes together. From October to November of 1986, they kidnapped and murdered four different women. On October 11th of 1986, they killed 32 year old Sandra Neary and on October 28th they killed 35 year old Pamela Simmons. Then on November 7th they Killed 20 year old Corina Novis and on November 12 they killed 19 year old Lionel Murray. They were both arrested just two days after killing Lynell. And when Cynthia was brought in for questioning, she immediately confessed to everything. At first she tried to tell police that James was abusing her and she was too scared to leave him and that she did not participate in the murders of the four women. But while she was in prison, she ended up confessing to her cellmate that she was absolutely in love with James and she did participate with all of the murders. In 1989 and 1990, Cynthia and James both went to trial where they were both found guilty of the murders of all four women and they were both sentenced to death. James is currently 68 years old and is serving his death sentence at the Richard J. Donovan Correctional Facility. Cynthia is currently 63 years old and is serving her death sentence at the Central California Women's Facility. And because she's in California, I don't think we will ever see her be executed. The next person on the list is 65 year old Carrie Dalton who has been serving a death sentence in California for the last 30 years. She was sentenced to death for the 1988 torture and murder of 23 year old Irene Melanie May. And still to this day Irene's body has never been found. On June 26 of 1988, Carrie and two other People, Cheryl Baker and Mark Tompkins were all together in a house with Irene. At some point, Carrie decided that Irene was a snitch and she eventually convinced both Mark and Cheryl that they all needed to kill her. Carrie decided that the best way to do this was to fill two syringes full of battery acid and then to inject Irene with those syringes. But when Irene wasn't immediately dying, they then began to be hit her over the head with a cast iron skillet and then they stabbed her several times. They then took her body and disposed of it. No one knows exactly how or what happened. And still to this day, her body has never been found. Both Mark and Cheryl cooperated with the detectives and told them everything that happened. And Mark Tomkins ended up pleading guilty to first degree murder and was sentenced to 25 years in prison. Cheryl Baker pled guilty to second degree murder and was sentenced to 15 years in prison. And I believe by now both of them have been released.

My parents stopped for my sister's Starbucks while driving me to the ER during my allergic reaction#ask#askreddit#LearnOnTikTok#reddit#satisfying#story#fyp#relaxing#fypã‚·
voice_to_text: My parents stopped for my sister's Starbucks while driving me to the er during my allergic reaction. I was 14 when I discovered I was deathly allergic to shellfish. We were at a family barbecue when someone brought shrimp skewers. Three bites in, my throat started closing. My lips swelled. Hives erupted across my arms. My cousin noticed first. Your neck, she said. Look at your neck. Red welts were crawling up from my collar. When I tried to call for help, my voice came out as a raspy whisper. My aunt found me collapsed against the sink. She screamed for my parents. Mom took one look and said, hospital now. We piled into the car, me in the backseat trying to remember how to breathe. Each inhale felt like sucking air through a coffee stirrer. We were maybe two miles from the hospital when my 11 year old sister piped up, can we stop at Starbucks? There's one right here. My vision was blurring and she wanted a Frappuccino. Not now, sweetie, mom said. But her voice was gentle. Negotiable, please, my sister whined. We're literally passing it. I tried to object but could only wheeze. Dad glanced at me in the rearview mirror. We have time, he said. She's still conscious. Still conscious. Those were the words he used to justify pulling into the Starbucks drive through while I was dying in the backseat. The line had six cars. Two minutes became four. Four became seven. My sister Ordered a venti caramel ribbon crunch with extra whipped cream. Mom reminded her to say please. Meanwhile, I was clawing at my throat, trying to force air into lungs that were sealing shut. The woman at the window noticed me. Is she okay? Just car sick, dad lied smoothly. When we finally pulled away, I'd lost feeling in my fingertips. The world was going gray. My sister took a long sip. Thanks, daddy, she said. Nine more minutes to the hospital. I spent them convinced I was going to die listening to her slurp her Starbucks. We screeched into the er bay. Within seconds, nurses surrounded us. I heard someone yell for an Epipen. The epinephrine hit my system like a defibrillator. A doctor leaned over me. You got here just in time, she said. Another few minutes and we'd be having a very different conversation. Just in time. We would have been there 10 minutes earlier if not for the Starbucks stop. But everyone was so relieved I was alive that no one wanted to talk about it. Later, my parents sat beside my hospital bed. We're so glad you're okay, mom said. We were terrified. My sister stood in the corner, still clutching her cup. She wouldn't make eye contact. The next day, they retold the story to relatives. We rushed her to the hospital, dad said. Didn't waste a single second. That was eight years ago. I'm 22 now and I carry two Epipens everywhere. I've had Three more severe allergic reaction since then, each time I drove myself to the hospital.

video_description: My husband assaulted me in front of his entire family and no one stood up to him, but my daughter#ask#askreddit#LearnOnTikTok#reddit#satisfying#story#fyp#relaxing#fypã‚·
voice_to_text: My husband assaulted me in front of his entire family and no one stood up to him. But my daughter did something that made him turn pale. It was Thanksgiving at his parents house and I should have known better than to show up with store bought dinner rolls. For eight years of marriage to Derek, I had Learned that everything had to be perfect in front of his family or there would be consequences later. But I had been pulling 12 hour shifts at the hospital all week and barely had time to shower, let alone bake homemade bread. His mother, Patricia, made the first comment. As I set the plastic container on her perfectly set dining table, she lifted one roll with her manicured fingers like it might contaminate her entire meal. Well, she said loud enough for the entire room to hear. I suppose not everyone has time for family traditions anymore. 22 family members were crammed into that dining room. His parents, both brothers with their wives, six kids ranging from toddlers to teenagers, and various aunts and uncle who had driven in from neighboring towns. All of them turned to stare at me like I had committed some unforgivable sin. I forced a smile and explained that I had been working overtime at the hospital. Three nurses had called in sick with the flu and someone had to cover the emergency department. I thought they would understand. His father was a retired police officer. His Brothers worked construction. They knew about demanding jobs. But Derek's face was already turning that familiar shade of red that meant trouble was coming. His jaw clenched the way it always did when he thought I had embarrassed him. The vein in his temple started throbbing. You always have an excuse, he said, loudly enough to cut through every conversation in the room. The football game on TV suddenly seemed too loud. Someone's fork clinked against their plate. One of the toddlers asked for more juice, but nobody moved to help him. All eyes were on us now. I'm not making excuses, I said as calmly as I could manage. I'm explaining why I didn't have time to bake this week. That's when he hit me. The slap echoed through the dining room like a gunshot. My cheek exploded in pain, and I could taste blood where my teeth had cut the inside of my lip. The force of it knocked me sideways, and I had to grab the back of a chair to keep from falling. Complete silence fell over the room. Not one person moved. Not one person spoke. His father stared at his plate like it held the secrets of the universe. His mother suddenly developed an intense interest in folding and refolding her napkin. His brothers exchanged a quick glance, but immediately looked away. Even the children had gone completely quiet. Don't you ever embarrass me like that again, Derek hissed through clenched teeth. That's when My 16 year old daughter Chloe stood up from the kids table in the corner. She had been living with us for two years since her father died in a motorcycle accident. Derek had never liked her, always complained that she was too mouthy, too independent, too much like me for his taste. She walked over slowly, deliberately, pulling her phone out of her back pocket as she moved. When she reached where Derek was standing, she held it up and aimed it directly at his face. Smile, she said with this.
